# TxMA Global Dashboard Health

The following dashboards represents an **overview** of the global health of TxMA as a whole. Dashboards unique to Individual TxMA products will be listed below.

Additional information about the dashboards

- `SQS Age of Oldest Message` 
  - messages older than a minute will be highlighted in yellow
  - messages older than 10 days will be highlighted in red. Queues in red need to be addressed immediately as messages older than 14 days will be removed. 
- `Lambda Error Rate` 
  - Any error above **1%** will turn the honeycomb red and should be investigated as all errors within TxMA should be handled gracefully
- Acronyms
  - `EP` - Event Processing
  - `QR` - Query Results
  - `SS` - Shared Signals 
- Apigateway metrics only cover the following AWS accounts
  - `di-txma-audit-prod`
  - `di-txma-query-results-prod`
  - `di-txma-shared-signals`

thresholds.columnId: LambdaFunction rate of failed invocations to all invocations %

# Additional Information

- Supporting TxMA is available in the [team manual](https://team-manual.account.gov.uk/teams/txma-team/)
- All dashboard where relevant will have thresholds from green, yellow and red. 
- Any metrics breaching the yellow threshold is cause for concern and any in red should be addressed by the TxMA team.
- The CSLS queues will have events in their queue as its part of tech debt to fix those queues
- the queues `self-production-EC-SQS*` are filled up with messages as expected.
- To get in touch with the TxMA team, visit `#di-ask-txma` in Slack

## Firehose Splunk Data Freshness

* How quickly TxMA is delivering events to a particular Splunk index
* Excessive time means Fraud or Performance team don't have current data
* TxMA expects it to take between 1-2 mins due to batching

tiles.name: Markdown
tiles.markdown:
## Firehose Splunk Throttling Count

The number of times firehose has throttled the rate at which data is being sent to Fraud

This is 0 most of the time. The line at 1 is the threshold.

tiles.name: Markdown
tiles.markdown:
## Self Serve Delivery Latency

The time it takes from an event coming into data platform to leaving the data platform
From the timestamp on the event to landing in the consumers output queue before consumers consume at their leisure


If someone has a time requirement, this would be the metric we refer to

Is a key contributer to the SLA that we do have which is 10 seconds to deliver a shared signal

One day AIS might ask for a 200ms SLA
